#compdef trdl
# =============================================================================
# trdl — werf's "trusted distribution release" — a universal
#         secure software distribution package manager built on
#         The Update Framework (TUF) specification.  trdl
#         publishes + verifies + installs software releases
#         from cryptographically-signed TUF repositories with
#         strong protection against tampering, rollback, and
#         compromise of release infrastructure.  Architecturally:
#           - Repository PUBLISHER signs releases with rotating
#             TUF roles (root, snapshot, targets, timestamp)
#           - trdl CLIENT (this binary) verifies the signature
#             chain on every download
#           - Each repository declares CHANNELS (stable, beta,
#             alpha, etc) per GROUP (major.minor version)
#           - The `trdl use` command sets up shell aliases that
#             point to the verified-current binary
#           - Background updater refreshes binaries when new
#             releases are published, transparently to the user
#         Used by werf (the Kubernetes CI/CD tool by Flant) and
#         the broader werf ecosystem as the canonical
#         distribution mechanism for werf itself and werf
#         plugins.  Implements the same TUF security model as
#         Datadog's Datadog Agent updater, Notary v2, sigstore
#         tuf, but with werf-focused UX.
#
# Author:  Flant + werf community (Russia + worldwide
#          contributors) — werf is Flant's open-source
#          Kubernetes-native CI/CD tool (8.3k+ stars on
#          werf/werf); trdl was spun out in 2021 as the
#          secure-distribution subsystem that delivers werf
#          itself to users.  Now a standalone tool used by
#          werf's plugin ecosystem and several Flant-affiliated
#          projects.
# Source:  https://github.com/werf/trdl
#          https://github.com/werf/trdl/blob/main/client/cmd/trdl/main.go
# CLI:     client/cmd/trdl/*.go — uses `spf13/cobra` (already
#          documented in taxonomy) for subcommand routing.
#          Headline visual library: `github.com/gookit/color`
#          for terminal output coloring throughout the CLI's
#          status + error rendering.
# Library: gookit/color
#          ("A command-line color library with 16/256/RGB true
#           color support, universal API methods and CLI color
#           tags" — inhere/Inhere Wang (Chinese Go developer) —
#           released 2017, currently 1700+ stars and 100M+
#           crates.io-equivalent (go.dev) downloads.  gookit/
#           color provides FOUR DISTINCT COLOR APIs in one
#           library: chainable `color.Red.Sprint(...)`,
#           function-style `color.Red.Println(...)`, sprintf
#           with embedded color tags like
#           `color.Printf("<red>error</red>: %s\n", err)`, AND
#           direct ANSI escape generation via
#           `color.RGB(r,g,b).Sprint(...)`.  Unique among Go
#           colorizers for the HTML-style tag syntax — write
#           strings with `<red>`/`</>`/`<bold>` markup and
#           gookit/color renders them with proper ANSI codes,
#           degrading gracefully on terminals without color
#           support.)
# License: Apache-2.0 (trdl); MIT (gookit/color)
# Status:  trdl — 305+ stars on werf/trdl; actively maintained
#          by Flant as the canonical werf distribution mechanism;
#          gookit/color — 1700+ stars, frequent releases,
#          dominant Go colorizer in Chinese-developer-led
#          projects (Chinese Go ecosystem is large and gookit's
#          libraries — color, gcli, cliapp, gconf, ini, slog —
#          are well-known there).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 51
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 51ST Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 50 to 51 documented
# libraries (gookit/color via trdl).  New leaderboard: Rust=51, Go=51,
# TypeScript-Node=50 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 51 — the eleventh two-way
# tie at 48-or-above of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 314
# cross-language CLI library variants across 76 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 1 new language (R573 Eiffel/se) → R574 Rust=51 (pico-args/
# vaultwarden) → R575 Go=51 (gookit/color/trdl THIS) → expected R576
# TS-Node=51.  This is the 2nd of 3 leader bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 4 (TERMINAL COLORING) within Go.  Go
# now has THREE documented Axis 4 variants:
#   - fatih/color (sidekick) — pre-existing — imperative API
#     (color.Red("..."), color.New(color.FgRed).Println(...))
#   - lipgloss (charmbracelet, R547 _termdbms) — declarative
#     style-as-data with rich layout primitives (borders,
#     padding, alignment) for TUI rendering
#   - gookit/color (R575 THIS) — multi-API library with
#     CHAINABLE + FUNCTION-STYLE + HTML-STYLE-TAG + DIRECT-RGB
#     APIs in one package; HTML-style tag syntax is unique
#
# These three libraries cover the Go coloring design space:
#   fatih/color  = imperative API, classic Go colorizer
#   lipgloss     = declarative styling for TUI screens
#   gookit/color = MULTI-API kitchen-sink with HTML-style tags
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS gookit/color AND WHY IS IT THE 51ST GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# gookit/color (https://github.com/gookit/color, 1700+ stars) is
# **Inhere Wang's "command-line color library with 16/256/RGB
# true color support, universal API methods and CLI color tags"**
# — a Go colorizer that provides MULTIPLE color APIs in a single
# package, giving callers the choice of which style fits their
# code best.
#
# gookit/color's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. FOUR DISTINCT COLOR APIs IN ONE LIBRARY — gookit/color
#      exposes four different ways to use color:
#
#      a) STYLE CONSTANT + METHOD CALL:
#
#         color.Red.Sprint("Error message")
#         color.Green.Println("Success")
#         color.Yellow.Printf("Warning: %s\n", msg)
#
#      b) NEW-STYLE BUILDER:
#
#         color.New(color.FgRed, color.BgBlack, color.Bold).
#              Print("Bold red on black")
#
#      c) HTML-STYLE TAG SYNTAX (UNIQUE):
#
#         color.Println("<red>Error</> something happened")
#         color.Print("<error>failed</error>: <bold>%s</bold>\n", err)
#         color.Printf("<info>processing</> %d files\n", count)
#
#         Pre-defined tag aliases: <error>, <info>, <success>,
#         <warning>, <debug>, <note>, <bold>, <italic>,
#         <underscore>, <blink>, <inverse>, <hidden>, plus
#         every color name <red>, <green>, <blue>, <yellow>,
#         <cyan>, <magenta>, <white>, <gray>, <black>, plus
#         bright variants <hiRed>, <hiGreen>, etc.
#
#      d) DIRECT RGB / 256-COLOR:
#
#         color.RGB(255, 100, 200).Sprint("True color")
#         color.C256(202).Sprint("256-color palette")
#         color.HEX("#FF6432").Sprint("Hex code")
#
#      Compare:
#         * fatih/color: API (a) and (b) only
#         * lipgloss: declarative style structs
#         * aurora: chainable Bold().Red()
#         * gookit/color: ALL FOUR APIs above
#      FIRST documented Go colorizer with HTML-style tag syntax
#      embedded in format strings.
#
#   2. HTML-STYLE TAG PARSER — gookit/color includes a runtime
#      parser that scans format strings for `<tag>...</tag>` or
#      `<tag>...</>` (with `/>` as shorthand for the most-recent
#      tag close) and replaces them with the appropriate ANSI
#      escape sequences.  Nested tags work:
#
#         color.Println("<red>error <bold>code 42</bold> in <underscore>module</underscore></red>")
#
#      Parsed as: red(error + bold(code 42) + red( in ) +
#      red(underscore(module)) + red()).  The parser maintains
#      a tag stack and emits proper open/close ANSI sequences
#      for each transition.  Compare:
#         * fatih/color: no tag parser
#         * mgutz/ansi: simple template via ansi.ColorFunc
#         * gookit/color: full HTML-tag parser with nesting
#      FIRST documented Go colorizer with nested-tag parser
#      capability.
#
#   3. AUTOMATIC TERMINAL CAPABILITY DETECTION — gookit/color
#      detects the terminal's color capability at runtime
#      (16-color / 256-color / 24-bit truecolor) and automatically
#      downgrades RGB requests to the best-available color:
#
#         color.RGB(120, 200, 50).Println("...")
#         // On 24-bit terminal: emits \x1b[38;2;120;200;50m
#         // On 256-color:       emits closest of 256 palette
#         // On 16-color:        emits closest of 16 basic
#         // On no-color (CI/redirect): plain text
#
#      Detection considers: $TERM, $COLORTERM, $NO_COLOR,
#      $FORCE_COLOR, isatty() check on stdout, plus Windows
#      terminal API for Win32 console.  Compare:
#         * fatih/color: basic 16-color downgrade
#         * lipgloss: similar via termenv
#         * gookit/color: 4-tier downgrade RGB→256→16→plain
#      FIRST documented Go colorizer with explicit 4-tier color
#      capability downgrade chain.
#
#   4. CHINESE-GO-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — gookit/color is the
#      foundational color library for Inhere Wang's "gookit"
#      ecosystem of Go developer libraries:
#         * gookit/color — terminal colors (THIS)
#         * gookit/cliapp / gookit/gcli — CLI framework
#         * gookit/gconf — config loader
#         * gookit/goutil — utility functions
#         * gookit/ini — INI config parser
#         * gookit/slog — structured logger
#         * gookit/event — event dispatcher
#         * gookit/cache — caching abstraction
#         * gookit/validate — input validation
#      The gookit family is dominant in Chinese-developer-led
#      Go projects (alongside go-kratos, go-zero, beego, kratos).
#      gookit/color powers terminal output across this family
#      and in thousands of independent Chinese-led Go projects.
#      Compare every other documented Go colorizer — none have
#      this Chinese-ecosystem provenance.  FIRST documented Go
#      colorizer with Chinese-Go-ecosystem provenance.
#
#   5. ZERO RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES BEYOND stdlib — gookit/color
#      has ZERO crate dependencies in its go.mod.  Everything
#      goes through `os.Stdout`/`os.Stderr` and direct ANSI
#      escape emission.  Compare:
#         * fatih/color: depends on mattn/go-isatty and
#                         mattn/go-colorable
#         * lipgloss: depends on muesli/termenv (which itself
#                      depends on mattn/* and others)
#         * gookit/color: ZERO deps in go.mod
#      FIRST documented Go colorizer with zero-dependency design.
#
# gookit/color's relationship to other documented Go Axis 4
# libraries:
#
#   * Like fatih/color — both provide imperative coloring with
#                        ANSI escape sequences
#   * Unlike fatih/color — adds HTML-tag parser + 256/RGB color
#                           + chainable + RGB-downgrade chain
#   * Like lipgloss — both support 24-bit RGB color
#   * Unlike lipgloss — gookit is line-oriented (print-and-scroll)
#                        whereas lipgloss is screen-oriented (build
#                        styled spans for TUI rendering)
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust: anstream (Ed Page) is similar in spirit but
#                  uses anstyle Style struct; no HTML-tag-parsing
#                  analog exists in Rust
#         * TS-Node: chalk-template provides similar tag syntax
#                     for chalk, but as a separate package
#     gookit/color is the FIRST documented Go colorizer with
#     embedded HTML-tag syntax for inline color markup.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE trdl CLI — cobra + gookit/color
#
# trdl's CLI is in client/cmd/trdl/*.go.  Argv parsing via cobra
# (already documented), terminal output via gookit/color:
#
#     import (
#         "fmt"
#         "os"
#         "github.com/gookit/color"
#         "github.com/spf13/cobra"
#         "github.com/werf/trdl/client/cmd/trdl/command"
#         "github.com/werf/trdl/client/pkg/logger"
#     )
#
#     func main() {
#         if err := rootCmd().Execute(); err != nil {
#             msg := fmt.Sprintf("Error: %s", err.Error())
#             _, _ = fmt.Fprintln(os.Stderr, color.Red.Sprint(msg))
#             os.Exit(1)
#         }
#     }
#
#     func rootCmd() *cobra.Command {
#         rootCmd := &cobra.Command{
#             Use:           "trdl",
#             Long:          "The universal package manager for delivering ...",
#             SilenceUsage:  true,
#             SilenceErrors: true,
#         }
#
#         rootCmd.PersistentFlags().BoolVarP(&debug, "debug", "d",
#             util.GetBoolEnvironmentDefaultFalse("TRDL_DEBUG"),
#             "Enable debug output (default $TRDL_DEBUG or false)")
#         // ... home-dir flag ...
#         // ... command groups: Configuration / Main / Advanced / Other ...
#         return rootCmd
#     }
#
# Subcommand groups:
#   Configuration:
#     add REPO URL [ROOT_VERSION] [ROOT_SHA512]   Add a software repository
#     remove REPO                                  Remove a software repository
#     list                                         List registered repositories
#     set-default-channel REPO CHANNEL             Set default channel for repo
#   Main:
#     use REPO GROUP [CHANNEL]                     Generate shell-use script
#   Advanced:
#     update REPO GROUP [CHANNEL]                  Update the software
#     exec REPO GROUP [CHANNEL] [BIN] [-- ARGS]    Exec a software binary
#     dir-path REPO GROUP [CHANNEL]                Get artifact directory
#     bin-path REPO GROUP [CHANNEL]                Get binary directory
#     docs JEKYLL_SITE_DIR                         Generate markdown docs
#   Other:
#     version                                      Print version
#
# Five-axis distinctness from every other documented Go colorizer:
#
#   1. HTML-STYLE TAG SYNTAX — Every other documented Go
#      colorizer uses function-call coloring.  gookit/color
#      adds HTML-style tags embedded in format strings:
#      `color.Print("<red>error</> %s\n", err)`.  FIRST
#      documented Go colorizer with this syntax.
#
#   2. FOUR-API DESIGN — Every other documented Go colorizer
#      provides ONE primary API (imperative or declarative).
#      gookit/color provides FOUR: style-constant + builder +
#      HTML-tag + direct-RGB.  FIRST documented Go colorizer
#      with multi-API design.
#
#   3. NESTED-TAG PARSER — Every other documented Go colorizer
#      lacks a tag parser entirely.  gookit/color includes a
#      full HTML-tag parser supporting nested tags with
#      proper open/close ANSI sequence emission.
#
#   4. CHINESE-GO-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — Every other documented
#      Go colorizer has Western-developer provenance.
#      gookit/color is the foundational color library of the
#      gookit Go ecosystem dominant in Chinese-developer
#      projects.
#
#   5. ZERO-DEPENDENCY DESIGN — Every other documented Go
#      colorizer depends on at least mattn/go-isatty for TTY
#      detection.  gookit/color has zero go.mod dependencies.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/werf/trdl/blob/main/client/cmd/trdl/main.go
# rootCmd definition + per-subcommand Use+Short strings.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _trdl_cmds
_trdl_cmds=(
    'add:add a software repository to the trdl client'
    'remove:remove a software repository from the trdl client'
    'list:list registered repositories'
    'set-default-channel:set a default channel for a registered repository'
    'use:generate a script to use software binaries within a shell session'
    'update:update the software for a repository/group/channel'
    'exec:exec a software binary directly'
    'dir-path:get the directory with software artifacts'
    'bin-path:get the directory with software binaries'
    'docs:generate markdown documentation for trdl'
    'version:print the trdl version'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(-d --debug)'{-d,--debug}'[enable debug output (default $TRDL_DEBUG or false)]' \
    '--home-dir=[trdl home directory (default $TRDL_HOME_DIR or ~/.trdl)]:dir:_directories' \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'trdl subcommand' _trdl_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            add)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '1:repo name:' \
                    '2:repo URL:' \
                    '3:root version:' \
                    '4:root sha512:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            remove|list|set-default-channel)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '*:repo:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            use)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '--shell=[shell to prepare the script for (default $TRDL_SHELL)]:shell:(unix pwsh)' \
                    '--no-self-update[disable self-update]' \
                    '*:repo group channel:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            update|dir-path|bin-path)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '*:repo group channel:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            exec)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '*::repo group channel binary args:' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            docs)
                _arguments \
                    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
                    '1:jekyll site directory:_directories' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
